When not to use Spark.

Spark earns its complexity only at scale, so before you reach for it, it is worth knowing when it is the wrong tool.

The first case: your data fits comfortably in pandas. Below roughly ten gigabytes on a modern laptop, pandas is faster, simpler, and carries no cluster overhead at all.

The second case: you need single-row, sub-millisecond lookups. Spark is optimized for throughput, not for latency. For that kind of work, reach for Postgres, or DynamoDB, or Redis.

The third case: you need online transaction processing semantics. Spark is built for analytical workloads that are read-heavy and write-batched. It is not a transactional database.

And the fourth case: you only need a scheduled script. Sometimes a cron job plus a plain Python script is exactly the right answer.

Here is the honest rule. Spark earns its complexity only when a single machine actually stops being enough — when scale, or fault tolerance, genuinely demand it.
